solutions.content:
Before going into details about how the solution works, you should have an understanding of the KMP algorithm.

In the KMP algorithm, we generate **lps[]** which represents the **longest proper prefix which is also suffix**. It tries to find the longest repetative pattern in given string. We can use this lps array to find out if given string can be created using pattern repeatedly.

Consider string **"ABABCD"** and its lps array. In the case of a string with continuous repeated pattern if we subtract lps[i] from the length of string till that point it will give us the length of the pattern. In the given image we can see that `length("ABAB") - lps[3] = 4-2 = 2` which is length of continuous repeated pattern **AB**.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/5e2eaadb-5865-4f02-a666-987ed6e4a9ee_1642328355.7733243.png)

Another example. String **"ABCABCABC"**.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/e4052dd9-4351-4fd2-9e17-02347ccc8f26_1642328467.3847742.png)

So, if the **length of string(n) % length of pattern(m) is zero** then we can say that the string can be constructed by taking a substring of it and appending multiple copies of the substring together. Where `length of pattern(m) = n - lps[n-1]`.

Java solution

```
class Solution {
    public boolean repeatedSubstringPattern(String s) {
        int n = s.length(), prevLPS = 0, i = 1;
        int[] lps = new int[n];
        while (i < n) {
            if (s.charAt(i) == s.charAt(prevLPS)) {
                lps[i++] = ++prevLPS;
            } else if (prevLPS == 0) {
                lps[i++] = 0;
            } else {
                prevLPS = lps[prevLPS - 1];
            }
        }
        return lps[n - 1] > 0 && n % (n - lps[n - 1]) == 0;
    }
}
```

