solutions.content:
I know the problem is somehow trivial, checking in a loop if your first character matches the following character, otherwise increasing the step and so on.

And as any respectable OCD-led engineer, I wanted to optimise it.

So I started to think what I could have done before to improve and avoid wasteful attempts.

And I decided first of all to get the frequency of all the characters, then take all those frequencies and compute the GCD of them with the always handy [Euclidean algorithm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm), setting the initial value of `base` to the overall length of the string itself, then reducing it while using all the non-`0` frequencies I found.

Say for example my frequencies for `'a'`, `'b'` and `'c'`, were, respectively, `6`, `15` and `18`: I would have known that the `base` tiniest repetition of all the character an even amount of time (in proportion to their distribution in the string) would have had length `3` (the GCD of those 3 frequencies); and later on we can assume that the tiniest substring we can start looking for it has to be equal to the overall string length (`6 + 15 + 18 == 39` in the example above) divided by this amount of repetitions (so the smallest possible pattern, if any such existed, would have been `39 / 3 == 13`).

Furthermore, if performing my GCD reduction would have resulted in `base == 1`, that would have told me that it was not possible to split the string into any sub-part of repeated characters, since the frequencies would have been prime compared to each other (ie: in the above example, getting for example `4`, `15` and `18`).

So, in a lot of cases, my pre-parse of the string already pays off its own cost, saving more hussle later on - I call it a win already!

But there is more: when we actually start to grind down and actually check for repeated patterns, instead of blindly trying in bits of `1`, `2`, etc..., we just move on in more sensible steps of `step` size, having computed it (initially) as `sLen / base` .

That is not trivial either, since in some more advanced tests, I obtained an initial `step` value of `5` or more, so definitely a lot of saved computation compared to going and testing our luck with all the numbers in the `1 - s.size() / 2` range.

Now, the last part is probably the easiest one: we initialise our `isRepeated` boolean to `true` because we feel optimistic (and because it is much less of a pain to check for mismatches in this kind of problem) and start looping:
* the outer loop will just go from `0` to `step` (excluded), that is to say with, say, `step == 13`, we would loop with `i` taking `0`, `1`, ... , `11` and `12` as values;
* the inner loop would compare the same character across all the supposed subpatterns, so, in our initial example, it will check in the first run if th characters in positions `0`, `13` and `26` all had the same value, then `1`, `14` and `27`, and so on;
* if any mismatch was found, we would flag `isRepeated` as `false`, break out of both loops;
* regardless of the reasonm once we are out of both loops we check; if `isRepeated` is `true`, then we also exit the while loop at once, otherwise we increase the `step` by `subStrLen`, all the time that we need so that `step` is still a valid divisor of `sLen` and then assign to `isRepeated` a value depending whether or not it has grown past half of the initial string length - if so, we are done checking and we exit.

At the end of it all, we just return the final value of `isRepeated` and we are done :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    // euclidean algorithm here, if you wonder
	int gcd(int a, int b) {
        return b ? gcd(b, a % b) : a;
    }
    bool repeatedSubstringPattern(string s) {
        int chars[26], sLen = s.size(), base = sLen;
        for (auto &c: chars) c = 0;
        for (char c: s) chars[c - 'a']++;
        for (int i: chars) if (i) base = gcd(base, i);
        // exit: no repeated substrings
        if (base == 1) return false;
        int subStrLen = sLen / base, step = subStrLen;
        // our result variable to be checked
        bool isRepeated = true;
        while (isRepeated) {
            for (int i = 0; i < step; i++) {
                for (int j = i; j < sLen; j += step) if (s[i] != s[j]) {
                    isRepeated = false;
                    break;
                }
                // if it is not a valid sequence, we exit here
                if (!isRepeated) break;
            }
            // if it is instead a valid sequence, here we exit for good
            if (isRepeated) break;
            // otherwise we try with a bigger step that is still a divisor of sLen
            do {
                step += subStrLen;
            } while (step <= sLen / 2 && sLen % step);
            // we reset isRepeated for another go
            isRepeated = step <= sLen / 2;
        }
        return isRepeated;
    }
};
```

